> Full project detection reference is in `docs/atdd/project-detection.md`.

## What to Detect

Before generating any code, detect:

1. **Language and package manager** — check for `package.json`, `pyproject.toml`, `*.csproj`, `go.mod`, `Cargo.toml`, `Gemfile`, etc.
2. **Test framework** — check deps, config files, existing test files and their naming patterns
3. **Linter** — ESLint, Biome, Ruff, Flake8, RuboCop, golangci-lint, Clippy
4. **Formatter** — Prettier, Biome, Black, rustfmt, gofmt
5. **Type checker** — TypeScript, mypy, pyright
6. **Build system** — npm scripts, Make, dotnet, go, cargo, gradle, maven
7. **CI/CD** — GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Jenkins, CircleCI
8. **Test conventions** — naming, directories, imports
9. **Existing project documentation** (mandatory if any docs exist) — read these **before**
   sampling code so they can point to canonical examples and override inference:
   - `README.md` (and variants) — setup/run/test commands, domain vocabulary
   - `CONTRIBUTING.md` — commit conventions, branch naming, PR process
   - `ARCHITECTURE.md` / `docs/architecture.md` — architecture style, module boundaries
   - `docs/adr/` or `docs/decisions/` — authoritative architectural decisions
   - `docs/` (other), `STYLE.md` / `STYLEGUIDE.md`, `SECURITY.md`,
     `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`

   Precedence: README overrides inferred commands; ADRs / `ARCHITECTURE.md` override inferred
   architecture; `CONTRIBUTING.md` overrides inferred commit/branch style; domain terms in
   docs must appear verbatim in specs and tests. Real conflicts go under `Known
   inconsistencies` in the profile.
10. **Code conventions** (mandatory for legacy projects) — sample 2–4 representative source
   files (ideally identified from step 9 hints) and extract:
   - Architecture style (layered, hexagonal, MVC, vertical slice, etc.)
   - Module layout (folder-by-feature vs folder-by-layer; co-located vs separated tests)
   - Dependency wiring (constructor DI, container, factories, plain imports)
   - Error handling (exceptions vs Result; custom error classes; boundary mapping)
   - Validation library and where validation lives
   - Async/cancellation patterns
   - Logging library and conventions
   - Configuration loading
   - Naming (files, classes, functions, constants, tests)
   - Public API style (REST/GraphQL/gRPC; URL casing; error format)
   - Persistence (ORM, migrations, transactions)
   - Commit and branch conventions

## Output

Write all findings to `docs/project-profile.md` with sections — `Tooling`, `Conventions`,
`Reference Files` (one file per layer the agent will mirror in Phase 3), and `Sources
consulted` (every doc and code file that informed the profile). Add `Known inconsistencies`
only when docs and code disagree. Record only what you observe — never guess.

## Adaptation Rules

- For legacy projects: match all existing conventions exactly; conventions discovery is
  non-negotiable
- For greenfield projects: prompt the user for tooling preferences (language, test framework,
  package manager, linter, formatter) in a single prompt before writing specs; the
  `Conventions` section starts empty
- Never replace existing configs — add alongside them
- Use the project's existing test framework, directory structure, and naming patterns
- The agent **must** re-read `docs/project-profile.md` before writing production code in
  Phase 3 and state which conventions it will follow

See also: `docs/atdd/legacy-integration.md`
